Simple Harmonic Motion

Simple harmonic motion can be demonstrated using a mass attached to a spring that is initially displacing and released to generate a spring force onto the mass, causing a type of periodic motion or oscillation.

The mass weight, spring strength and damping clearly effect the motion, but in what way? A Shiny application has been developed to allow you to explore the change in frequency given changes in mass, spring force and damping factor.

gif by Svjo (Own work) [CC BY-SA 3.0 (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0)]

Equation of Simple Harmonic Motion

The Shiny Application uses the Simple Harmonic Motion equation:

x = Acos(wt + α), where

  • x is the mass's displacement (in metres)
  • A is the starting Amplitude (in metres)
  • t is elapsed time (in seconds)
  • α is the phase shift (in radians)
  • w is the angular displacement (in radians)

w is calculated as: w=k m, where

  • m is mass of the weight (in kg)
  • k is the spring force (in N/m)

SHM with Viscous Damping

The application also calculates motion where viscous damping (ξ) is applied. Key equations used are:

Underdamped (ξ <1): X=Ae -ξwtcos (wdt- α)

Critical Damped (ξ =1): Ae- (wt)( 1+wt)

Overdamped (ξ >1): x=(A cosh (w st)+ Aξwsinh  (ws t)ws )e- ξwt

Where wd =w1- ξ2 and ws=w ξ2-1
